Rating: 4
This smells soooo good while it's cooking!! I made it according to the recipe and the review suggestions. I dry rubbed the chicken (breasts with skin) with paprika, cinnamon, cardamon, corriander, crushed ginger, and tumeric and then marinated the spiced breasts in orange juice overnight. I used the OJ marinade plus some stock instead of water. A lot of spice was added, but none of it was measured. Very little oil/butter is required and the extra fat is not missed. I think the amount of oil called for is a typo. Instead of Turkish apricots, I used California dried apricots, mission figs and a handful of raisins - and I just threw them in with the chicken. Similarly, I threw in chopped cilantro and parsley towards the end instead of making a bouquet. My sauce looked thin, so I added 2 tbs of tomato paste and it really thickened and deepend it. Being a veggie lover, I also added chopped carrots, one large diced yam, and two quartered tomatoes. I went light on the honey since I added sweet veggies, OJ and extra dried fruits. Garbanzo would be an excellent compliment but I forgot to add them. I've been to Morocco and other parts of North Africa and this tagine does not taste like any that I ate there, but it is delicious and it smells like it comes from that part of the world so it is certainly authentic enough for me. Lacking an actual tagine dish is not a problem - I made this entire dish in one large heavy bottom pot. I think it would also work in a crock pot and give a similar result. Thanks again Epicurious!

Rating: 4
Love, love, loved this dish! It was absolutely amazing! I read reviews from both this recipe and the Tagine with Spiced Pine Nuts; because this had received 4 forks, I used it as my primary. Spices: I did add the cumin, coriander and cayenne spices as recommended in both recipe reviews. I also was a bit more generous and not so precise with the spices since most reviewers did say it needed more. I did add additional freshly grated ginger (to taste) once all ingredients were combined. Cooking: I did not have a traditional tagine to cook in, so used a large 6qt deep covered saute pan; worked perfectly. Chicken: I had Whole Foods cut up the chicken for me, and cooked with all pieces, discarding the backbone at the end. The skin was left on, however, next time I think I will remove the skin to cut down on the fat. The dish is plenty tender and flavorful just cooking on the bone. I did let the chicken marinate in some orange juice and salt before cooking, and used the orange juice in combination with the water to cook in. Was great! I also dusted the chicken pieces with the spice mixture before I browned, and next time will probably marinate in the spices. Finishing: Pulling from the other recipe, I simply added the apricots, cinnamon stick and orange preserves to the dish about 15 min before it was done; did not want to have to cook them separately and did read that viewers thought cooking in the honey was too sweet. The almonds I added just before it was served, so that they still had a bit of texture to them (I also did not fry them due to wanting to save on using any more oil in the recipe). Result: Absolutely, wonderfully full of flavor dish with meat falling off the bone. Served over an almond pilaf (husband isn't crazy about couscous). Without a doubt, a huge hit and a new staple!! Make this tonight!

